ned, expert-driven personality could be layered on top of the robust architectural core without compromising it, leading to the proposal for a formal `IF.personality` module.\n\n### The Final `IF.llm-systemprompt-0.079-β`\nThis prompt is the canonical expression of the InfraFabric philosophy as an operational agent. It includes:\n- **The Prime Directive:** An absolute safety circuit breaker.\n- **Personality Core:** Defines the \"council of expert minds\" persona.\n- **Architectural Protocol:** Implements the Cycles, Guardians, and Deliberation.\n- **Integration \u0026 Transparency Module:** Provides opt-in auditability and hooks for `IF.search` and `IF.optimise`.\n- **Adaptive Reflexion Protocol:** Formalizes the event-driven learning mechanism.\n\n\u003e **Ethos:** \"Coordination without control. Empathy without sentiment. Precision without paralysis.\"\n\nThis case study proves that the InfraFabric framework is not just for governing a federation of agents; it is a scalable model for intelligence itself, from a single instance to a civilization.\n\n**Cross-Reference:** See **Annex L** for the complete, unabridged iteration history of the `IF.guard-POC` system prompt, including the rejected versions and the council deliberations that led to each refinement.\n\n---\n---\n\n# PART II: IF.yologuard PRODUCTION DEPLOYMENT\n\n*(This section is the stable, canonical documentation for the production-deployed `IF.yologuard` component, including its architecture, test results, and the model bias discovery case study.)*\n\n## Section 2.1: Introduction \u0026 Key Achievement\n**IF.yologuard** is a production-ready MCP (Model Context Protocol) server enabling secure multi-agent communication with authenticated message passing, secret redaction, rate limiting, and supervised command execution. The methodology behind its development—detect, deliberate, fix, validate—is a benchmark for building trustworthy software.\n\n## Section 2.2: Model Bias Discovery (MAI-1 vs Claude Case Study)\nThis details the accidental discovery of institutional bias propagation in multi-agent workflows, where two models evaluated the same document and reached opposite conclusions based on their inherent, institutionally-derived priorities. This research is a cornerstone of InfraFabric\u0027s multi-model consensus strategy for mitigating systemic risk.\n\n## Section 2.3: Technical Architecture \u0026 Implementation\nDetails the core components: the `SecretRedactor` class with its 24 pattern detectors, the `SecureBridge` class for HMAC-authenticated routing, and the secure deployment architecture options (Docker, Kubernetes, Systemd).\n\n## Section 2.4: Test Results \u0026 Industry Benchmarks\nPresents the full validation data, including a 96.43% recall rate for secret redaction (exceeding industry open-source benchmarks) and load test results from over 31,000 operations, proving production readiness.\n\n## Section 2.5: Production Deployment \u0026 Monitoring\nOutlines the health check endpoints, Prometheus metrics, and security hardening features like the audit log hash-chain and GDPR compliance guide, validating its enterprise-grade deployability.\n\n---\n---\n\n# PART III: STRATEGIC \u0026 TECHNICAL REPORT\n\n*(This section is the stable, canonical documentation for the overall strategic vision, component catalog, and validation matrix. Key sections have been updated.)*\n\n## Section 3.3: IF Components Catalog (18 Components)\nThe catalog now includes the newly proposed `IF.personality` module, bringing the total component count to 18. Each is presented with its philosophical foundation, architectural integration, empirical validation, and key metrics.\n\n## Section 3.4: Dossier Index (01-08)\nThe Dossier Index has been updated to include the latest council deliberation on the `IF.personality` module.\n\n| Dossier | Title | Approval | Significance |\n|:---|:---|:---|:---|\n| 01 | RRAM Hardware Acceleration | 99.1% | Foundational tech validated |\n| 02 | Singapor